    <h1>Building a Strong Safety Culture</h1>
  </header>

  <main>
    <h2>What is Safety Culture?</h2>
    <p>Safety culture refers to the shared values, attitudes, and behaviors of an organization 
      towards safety. It reflects the commitment of everyone, from leadership to employees, 
      to prioritize safety in all aspects of work.</p>

    <h2>Benefits of a Strong Safety Culture</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Reduced accidents and injuries</li>
      <li>Improved employee morale and well-being</li>
      <li>Enhanced productivity and efficiency</li>
      <li>Reduced costs associated with workplace incidents</li>
      <li>Positive reputation and brand image</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Key Elements of a Strong Safety Culture</h2>

    <section class="safety-elements">
      <article>
        <h3>Leadership Commitment</h3>
        <p>Leaders set the tone for safety by demonstrating a genuine commitment to 
          protecting employees and providing necessary resources.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>Employee Engagement</h3>
        <p>Active participation and open communication from employees are crucial for 
          identifying and addressing safety hazards.</p>
      </account>
      <article>
        <h3>Continuous Improvement</h3>
        <p>A strong safety culture is constantly evolving. Regularly reviewing practices and 
          implementing improvements are essential.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>Accountability and Recognition</h3>
        <p>Holding everyone accountable for safety practices and recognizing positive safety 
          behaviors reinforces a culture of safety.</p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <h2>Building a Strong Safety Culture: Getting Started</h2>
    <p>Here are some steps your organization can take:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Develop and communicate a clear safety policy.</li>
      <li>Provide regular safety training and awareness programs.</li>
      <li>Empower employees to report safety concerns without fear of reprisal.</li>
      <li>Investigate all incidents thoroughly and implement corrective actions.</li>
      <li>Celebrate safety successes and milestones.</li>
    </ol>

